---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import { useTranslations } from '../../i18n/utils';
import Animations from '../../components/Animations.vue';

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [
    { params: { lang: 'en' } },
    { params: { lang: 'es' } },
    { params: { lang: 'pt' } },
  ];
}

const { lang } = Astro.params;
const t = useTranslations(lang);

const content = {
  en: {
    title: "Dear Diary, I Kept Hearing Node.js Was Insecure 🌸",
    date: "June 22, 2026",
    subtitle: "A developer diary by Jill",
    back: 'Back to Home',
    intro: "For a while I kept hearing the same thing over and over.",
    introDesc: `"Node.js has too many vulnerabilities." "Node isn't secure." "Don't use Node for serious applications."`,
    introExtra: [
      "And honestly—",
      "I believed it.",
      "Because if enough developers repeat something…",
      "it starts sounding true.",
      "But the more I worked with real projects…",
      "the more I realized something.",
      "The conversation was more complicated than I thought."
    ],
    firstAssumption: {
      heading: "My first wrong assumption",
      paragraphs: [
        "I thought Node.js itself was the problem.",
        "Like somewhere inside Node there was a giant red button labeled: <strong>security issues</strong>.",
        "Turns out—",
        "most of the conversation isn't about Node.",
        "It's about everything around it.",
        "Packages. Dependencies. Versions. Configurations.",
        "And suddenly the villain became much less dramatic."
      ]
    },
    discovery: {
      heading: "Discovery of the day",
      paragraphs: [
        "Node applications rarely exist alone.",
        "A typical application might look like:",
        "Your Application → Framework → Dependencies → Dependencies of dependencies → More dependencies → Even more dependencies.",
        "And suddenly:",
        "one vulnerable package somewhere deep in the tree…",
        "becomes your problem.",
        "That was the moment I understood.",
        "Node didn't suddenly become insecure.",
        "Its ecosystem became very large."
      ]
    },
    techNotes: {
      heading: "Technical Notes ✨",
      intro: "Things I learned while researching and working with Node environments.",
      notes: [
        {
          title: "1. Installing one package installs… many packages",
          before: "npm install package-name",
          beforeLabel: "Sometimes this:",
          after: "1 package\n↓\n32 dependencies\n↓\n145 subdependencies\n↓\nDone",
          afterLabel: "actually becomes:",
          note: "Which means: you didn't install one thing. You installed an entire family tree."
        },
        {
          title: "2. Vulnerabilities are often discovered later",
          before: null,
          beforeLabel: null,
          after: "Version 2.4.0\n↓\nSecurity issue discovered\n↓\nCVE published\n↓\nUpdate recommended",
          afterLabel: "A dependency may be fine today. Then months later:",
          note: "CVE = Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures. Basically: a public catalog of known security issues. That was terrifying and fascinating."
        },
        {
          title: "3. npm already gives tools to help",
          before: "npm audit",
          beforeLabel: "One command I discovered:",
          after: "3 vulnerabilities found\n\n1 low\n1 moderate\n1 high",
          afterLabel: "Example output:",
          extraCode: "npm audit fix",
          extraLabel: "And then:",
          note: "Tries to update what can safely be fixed. Not magic. But useful."
        },
        {
          title: "4. Updating everything blindly is not security",
          before: null,
          beforeLabel: null,
          after: "- release notes\n- breaking changes\n- compatibility\n- package activity",
          afterLabel: "Usually people review:",
          note: "This one surprised me. I assumed: more updates = safer. Not always. Sometimes updates break things. Which felt annoyingly responsible."
        },
        {
          title: "5. Not every problem needs another dependency",
          before: null,
          beforeLabel: null,
          after: "Array.map()\nfetch()\nDate()",
          afterLabel: "When JavaScript already had:",
          note: "This one hurt a little. I realized sometimes I searched \"How do I install a package to do this?\" when the answer was already built in. And suddenly I understood why people joke about installing 200 packages."
        }
      ]
    },
    nobodyWarned: {
      heading: "The part nobody warned me about",
      paragraphs: [
        "Security isn't usually dramatic.",
        "Nobody breaks into your app wearing a hoodie.",
        "Most of the time it looks like:",
        "outdated package. weak configuration. old environment variable. missing validation. forgotten dependency.",
        "Which somehow feels less cinematic."
      ]
    },
    click: {
      heading: "When it finally clicked ✨",
      paragraphs: [
        "At some point I stopped asking:",
        ""Is Node insecure?"",
        "And started asking:",
        ""What am I trusting?"",
        "That changed the way I look at projects.",
        "Because every install is also a decision.",
        "Every dependency becomes part of your system.",
        "And every shortcut eventually becomes maintenance."
      ]
    },
    bonus: {
      heading: "Bonus: Things I now pay more attention to",
      intro: "Before adding a dependency:",
      flowItems: [
        "Can I build this?",
        "Is it maintained?",
        "Does it have recent releases?",
        "How many downloads?",
        "Open security issues?",
        "Do I really need it?"
      ],
      note: "Not because everything is dangerous. But because everything has tradeoffs."
    },
    personalNote: {
      heading: "Personal note 🌸",
      paragraphs: [
        "As an Aries, discovering my application secretly contained 300 packages felt personally offensive.",
        "I installed one thing.",
        "One.",
        "Why do we suddenly have an ecosystem."
      ]
    },
    realLesson: {
      heading: "The real lesson 💖",
      paragraphs: [
        "Node.js didn't suddenly become insecure.",
        "I just started understanding that modern development isn't only writing code.",
        "It's also choosing what code to trust.",
        "And honestly—",
        "that feels like a much more interesting problem."
      ]
    },
    remember: {
      heading: "Things I Want To Remember 🌷",
      items: [
        "Dependencies are part of architecture",
        "Updating deserves strategy",
        "Security is usually accumulation",
        "Simplicity reduces risk",
        "Every install is a decision"
      ]
    },
    closing: "Next entry: Apparently I'm Human",
    closingSign: "See you in the next entry ✨",
    signature: "— Jill"
  },
  es: {
    title: "Querido Diario, Seguía Escuchando Que Node.js Era Inseguro 🌸",
    date: "22 de Junio, 2026",
    subtitle: "El diario de desarrollo de Jill",
